Remap cross-compile include paths so the ffmpeg-sys-next feature probe
compiles for the host architecture (no QEMU required).

Upstream (zmwangx/rust-ffmpeg-sys 8.1.0) compiles the `check.c` feature
probe with `.target(env::var("HOST"))` so the resulting ELF executes
natively on the build host. This is correct in spirit -- the probe only
reads compile-time `#define` constants from ffmpeg headers (feature
flags, version macros), which are architecture-independent.

But cross-compile breaks because pkg-config returns the *target's*
arch-specific include paths (e.g. `/usr/include/aarch64-linux-gnu`).
Passing those to the host x86_64 compiler pulls in foreign-arch system
headers transitively -- glibc 2.39's `<bits/math-vector.h>` declares
`__neon_vector_type__` / `__SVFloat32_t` SVE types, and the host clang
chokes.

This patch remaps the target arch directory in each `-I` path to the
host arch equivalent (e.g. `aarch64-linux-gnu` → `x86_64-linux-gnu`).
The ffmpeg headers are byte-identical between Ubuntu's amd64 and arm64
libavcodec-dev packages of the same version, so the probe produces the
same feature-detection output. The host compiler now only sees its
own system headers and compiles cleanly.

Why not require qemu-user-static + binfmt: container/CI environments
often lack the privileged binfmt registration step, and our Docker
image already ships qemu-user-static but Docker hosts on bare metal
frequently don't have it installed. Compiling natively removes the
whole dependency chain.

Patched into the vendored submodule by `make apply-vendored-patches`
(invoked transitively by `rust-build` / `rust-test` / `rust-lint`).
Idempotent: skipped if the patched marker is already present.

--- a/build.rs
+++ b/build.rs
@@ -793,9 +793,35 @@ fn check_features(
         .get_compiler()
         .to_command();

+    // When cross-compiling, pkg-config returns include paths for the target
+    // arch (e.g. /usr/include/aarch64-linux-gnu). Passing those to the host
+    // compiler pulls in foreign-arch system headers that fail to compile
+    // (aarch64 NEON intrinsics, SVE types, etc.). Since ffmpeg's public
+    // headers are arch-independent, remap target include paths to the host
+    // equivalent so the probe compiles natively.
+    let host = env::var("HOST").unwrap_or_default();
+    let target = env::var("TARGET").unwrap_or_default();
+    let cross = host != target;
+    let host_arch_dir = if host.starts_with("x86_64") {
+        "x86_64-linux-gnu"
+    } else if host.starts_with("aarch64") {
+        "aarch64-linux-gnu"
+    } else {
+        ""
+    };
+
     for dir in include_paths {
         compiler.arg("-I");
-        compiler.arg(dir.to_string_lossy().into_owned());
+        let dir_str = dir.to_string_lossy().into_owned();
+        if cross && !host_arch_dir.is_empty() {
+            let remapped = dir_str
+                .replace("aarch64-linux-gnu", host_arch_dir)
+                .replace("x86_64-linux-gnu", host_arch_dir)
+                .replace("arm-linux-gnueabihf", host_arch_dir);
+            compiler.arg(remapped);
+        } else {
+            compiler.arg(dir_str);
+        }
     }
     if !compiler
         .current_dir(&out_dir)
